I don't really mean to be guarded. I feel like an open book with shifting walls, like the stars have to align for people to be able to come read the book.

This is also compounded by the fact that I do have fairly regular depression spells so a lot of the time me feeling like dog shit isn't real and will pass and has no real trigger. But it can be hard to separate those times from real times with tangible triggers

But in reality that just means that people never know where I'm at with stuff. I don't explain why my job is bugging me or why my coworker is stupid or why I'm feeling a certain way typically until it's already over.

But in the end, none of it ever came to be. They were just musings or half baked ideas. I don't want to put that on other people. I don't want people to change their thoughts or make plans around things that might not happen, so I don't say things unless I'm certain about them

I'd intake that information and start making plans around it and letting it saturate my mind. "We're moving to Florida" "We're moving to New York" "I have cancer and you need to learn to live without me" (they did not end up having cancer.)
Part of it is being raised by someone who would dump their plans and aspirations for the future on me all the time, even if those plans weren't likely to see fruition at all.

Though, let's be honest, I have trouble expressing myself in general these days. I don't really see my thoughts as carrying much value or being worth expressing so I don't. I tend not to say things unless I think they carry enough weight to matter.
When Josh and Ash asked me how I felt about things after we'd watched them I was always just like "Ugh. Ooga Booga. Grug sense much pain in James Sunderland."
I suppose this is 1am drunken vent-time erasure but that's rare these days

Maybe I have trouble connecting with people anymore because the main time I want to connect with people is between the hours of 9am and Noon. My brain tendrils reach out the most then, but all of my friends are evening people. Bruh I'm in bed by 8...
Feel like I only tweet my actual brainthoughts early in the morning, fueled by coffee and vyvanse, lmao.

@Addark Good on whoever got you that book. I think when I raise a kid, I'll make sure to get them a book or two like that. "Critical Thinking" can be daunting to teach because its such a broad concept, but you really can break it down into its simplest parts--

Though, without wearing too big of a tinfoil hat, The Man presiding over education clearly does not want the vast majority of people to have good critical thinking skills, lest the populace grow smart enough to see through the bullshit.

I suppose the big question then is what class to teach them in, but really, you could form those puzzles to work in any class setting...English, math, history, science. I could see applications for them in all of them.

One of the more common strings I heard in nursing school was that students had "poor critical thinking skills" and a lot of it came down to not being able to use deductive reasoning well, or to take information given and turn it into a solution. Simple logic puzzles would help.

When I was in 'gifted kid' classes, one of the more common things we did were logic puzzles. Sort of like verbal algebra. If this, then that, if that, then this, etc. I never did them in any other class, though, and I really think that was a failing of the education system.
